posts.name: joel truher
posts.cooked: Our recent memory-error adventures led me to implement proguard tree-shaking, which shrinks the output jar by about 50%.  Anybody else use proguard?   It’s “normal” for things like android apps, but i haven’t heard of folks using it in FRC.

posts.name: Sam Maier
posts.cooked:
Proguard is not likely to significantly change memory usage. You will get a small amount of memory back from the ClassLoader having a smaller lookup table, but chances are your actual program uses orders of magnitude more memory than the overhead of the dead code.

The main reason to use proguard/r8 is disk space, which is not something I’ve heard an FRC team struggle with. And, if your team or any library your team pulls in uses reflection (WPIlib seems to use a tiny amount) you run the risk of confusing runtime crashes.

posts.name: joel truher
posts.cooked:
yeah, that makes sense, thanks.  the lead we were hunting was that the jvm would fail to mmap an amount that looked a lot like the jar size, so we thought making it smaller would help.

as it turned out the only thing that helped was replacing the roborio, which is super strange.
